SIMPLE: most
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Most
<hw>Most</hw> <pr>(m⟦omac⟧st)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos>, <pos>superl.</pos> of
<er>More</er>. <ety>[OE. <ets>most</ets>, <ets>mast</ets>,
<ets>mest</ets>, AS. <ets>m⟦aemac⟧st</ets>; akin to D. <ets>meest</ets>,
OS. <ets>m⟦emac⟧st</ets>, G. <ets>meist</ets>, Icel. <ets>mestr</ets>,
Goth. <ets>maists</ets>; a superl. corresponding to E. <ets>more</ets>.
⟦root⟧103. See <er>More</er>, <pos>a.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>Consisting of the greatest number or quantity; greater in number or
quantity than all the rest; nearly all.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧<xex>Most</xex> men
will proclaim every one his own goodness.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Prov. xx.
6.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The cities wherein <qex>most</qex> of his mighty works were
done.</q> <rj><qau>Matt. xi. 20.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Greatest in degree; <as>as, he has the <ex>most</ex>
need of it</as>.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧In the <xex>moste</xex> pride.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Highest in rank; greatest.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
<rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ <xex>Most</xex> is used as a noun, the words
<xex>part</xex>, <xex>portion</xex>, <xex>quantity</xex>, etc., being
omitted, and has the following meanings: <b>1.</b> The greatest value,
number, or part; preponderating portion; highest or chief part.
<b>2.</b> The utmost; greatest possible amount, degree, or result;
especially in the phrases <xex>to make the most of</xex>, <xex>at the
most</xex>, <xex>at most</xex>.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A quarter of a year or some months <qex>at the most</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Bacon.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A covetous man <qex>makes the most of</qex> what he has.</q>
<rj><qau>L'Estrange.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>For the most part</b></col>, <cd>in reference to the
larger part of a thing, or to the majority of the persons, instances, or
things referred to; as, human beings, <xex>for the most part</xex>, are
superstitious; the view, <xex>for the most part</xex>, was
pleasing.</cd> -- <col><b>Most an end</b></col>, <cd>generally. See
<cref>An end</cref>, under <er>End</er>, <pos>n.</pos></cd>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> ⟦ldquo⟧She sleeps <xex>most an end</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Massinger.</au></rj></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Most</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Most
<hw>Most</hw>, <pos>adv.</pos> <ety>[AS. <ets>m⟦aemac⟧st</ets>. See
<er>Most</er>, <pos>a.</pos>]</ety> <def>In the greatest or highest
degree.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Those nearest to this king, and <qex>most</qex> his favorites,
were courtiers and prelates.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ Placed before an adjective or adverb, <xex>most</xex> is
used to form the superlative degree, being equivalent to the termination
<xex>-est</xex>; as, <xex>most</xex> vile, <xex>most</xex> wicked;
<xex>most</xex> illustrious; <xex>most</xex> rapidly. Formerly, and
until after the Elizabethan period of our literature, the use of the
double superlative was common. See <er>More</er>,
<pos>adv.</pos></note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The <qex>most unkindest</qex> cut of all.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The <qex>most straitest</qex> sect of our religion.</q>
<rj><qau>Acts xxvi. 5.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mostahiba</ent>⟦br⟧
